const e=`Everyone knows Cellino & Barnes, but how about Michael the Bull, Yo Pain Law Yo (Harris, Keenan & Goldfarb), Moorejustice (Darren Moore), Mikhael Ilyaich, Every Borough Every Block (Shulman Hill)? It seems as though overnight there has been an influx of legal ads in the subway, all personal injury. Apart from laughing at HKG's attempt at being relatable to New Yorkers, seeing these numerous new ads got me thinking about the potential success of subway advertising and why in particular for this type of law.

These ads fit so naturally into the subway ecosystem, alongside dating apps, delivery food, and housing ads because they so well represent New Yorkers' everyday thoughts. Yet, law firms lay at an interesting intersection as private corporations that sell themselves as protection from private corporations; their ads seem one leg in justice and one in the money bubble. All of these firms focus on personal injury, but the language of their page tells us a bit about why there is a rise in their marketing now and how they wish to be received.

Each has a tab for sample results and successes to showcase the prowess of their litigation. Perhaps most iconically, Cellino Law was established in 1998 with a particular focus on the injury itself. Their sample results have a small heading of the settlement number above specific details of horrible accidents such as one plaintiff who suffered from spinal injuries and had lumbar and cervical spinal fusion operations, and developed Complex Regional Pain Syndrome.[1]

Other firms, for instance Harris, Keenan & Goldfarb and Mikhael Ilyaich, also have specific descriptions of the injuries themselves for their highlighted cases. On the other hand, Darren Moore and Michael Lamonsoff's offices put much more emphasis on the large settlements and opt to describe the prosecutor's situation as simply injury. For these firms, the numbers and dollar signs are bold and large.

America has long been seen as the country to jump onto any possibility of a lawsuit, to many other cultures, undeserved and deceitful money making rather than compensation for injustice. When the highlight of their sites is compensation, Michael the Bull's mission statement, for example, is honest: "While no amount can undo trauma, we fight for maximum compensation and lasting peace of mind."

This tension is not only what makes lawyers a common subject of scorn, but in its reconciliation, we may understand why there are suddenly so many of these ads. Lawsuits were seen as greedy because money was framed as corrupting justice. Take the McDonald's hot coffee case, infamous for a woman who burned herself with coffee and was rewarded with a fat payout. The reality was that McDonald's had been negligent toward hundreds of complaints about the temperature of the coffee, and the woman suffered from third degree burns because of it. With that knowledge, rather than being shameful, the lawsuit was an effort that reliably produced consequences.

Still, the prominence of these million-dollar payouts does not erase their association with excess. Rather, it reframes excess as credibility. In an economy where scale is equated with seriousness, large settlements signal not just success, but authority. It starts to feel like personal injury lawyers are being rebranded as one of the last accessible forms of accountability in a city, and country, where institutional trust has eroded.

As trust in government shifts, so does the perception of lawyers. In an increasingly polarized political climate, to many, public institutions may feel less representative of working people and more aligned with private enterprise. For example, major enforcement actions against large tech and advertising companies have recently been dropped by the Federal Trade Commission, even as the agency's independence has been weakened by political turnover.[2]

Similarly, President Donald Trump's one million dollar per plate Mar-a-Lago dinners and five million dollar one-on-one meetings with business leaders have given private actors an outsized influence over policy decisions.[3] Corporations are everywhere yet rarely accountable, and when the systems meant to regulate them feel ineffective, litigation becomes one of the few legible forms of agency, not just a path to compensation.

In a time where backroom deals not only come to light but are commonly accepted, these ads work to promise an individualized mechanism for retribution. The personal injury a plaintiff would file for doesn't simply refer to itself but represents the general economic precarity they face every day, from ACA medical insurance rates increasing by a median of 18% in 2026[4] to 25 percent of New Yorkers living below the poverty line.[5]

Thus, the lawsuit is not just about the accident but about life lived without a safety net. The particular words of the ads, "ACCIDENT?" (Mikhael Ilyaich), or the picture of subway chairs while being displayed in the subway by Shulman Hill, speak to the redundancy that New Yorkers can find amusing but also feel seen. Lawyers are not just for the private sector but for the public and for the individual. These advertisements capitalize on that sentiment.

Subway ads work because there is no escape. You can ignore an Instagram ad with a flick of your thumb, but on the train you're pressed between backpacks, pretending to answer emails, waiting for the doors to open. The same poster watches you every morning until one day it disappears, quietly replaced by an AI startup you won't remember or another sudden Wonder takeover.

Personal injury ads feel oddly appropriate in this setting. They don't interrupt moments of optimism; they meet you at your least aspirational, halfway between work and exhaustion. The humor at least dulls the edge. Cellino & Barnes' jingle, "WHEN DIAMONDS AREN'T FOREVER," Michael the Bull's unwavering stare: serious injuries packaged just lightly enough to be digestible before your first coffee. After a while, they stop feeling like ads and start feeling like part of the route.

Of course, the promise is exaggerated. Multimillion-dollar settlements are rare, justice is slower than the Q train, and money rarely repairs what it claims to. Still, there's something comforting about the clarity in a face that's just a phone number away. In a city where institutions feel distant and accountability abstract, these ads offer the illusion of a direct line.

The subway ad doesn't promise fairness. It promises that if something goes wrong, there's at least someone you can call. Whether or not that's justice is another question, but lately, it seems close enough to sell.
`;export{e as default};
